So a cow that meets an equaly quick and arguably painless death suffers more? <br>
<br>
Trying to push being a Vegitarian because you think its &quot;healthy&quot; is one thing. Trying to push it because of the &quot;poor animals&quot; is another. <br>
<br>
Ive shot moose, did I feel pity for them? No I did not nor should I. Its not like the moose's poker buddys are gonna miss him next friday night. His wife isn't going to wonder when he is going to come home. And his kids being beasts driven by instinct alone don't even know they have a father in the true sense of the word.<br>
<br>
Did he feel pain? im sure he did, right up to the point I put a 30 ot six round through his eye. When you can prove to me that a unthinking beast has other unthinking beasts that will truly mourn his passing then ill rethink hunting meat. The same moose runs the risk of being slowly eaten alive by a bear every day of its life. Or breaking a leg and being draged down by a pack of wolfs and eaten to death. Or better yet starving to death during the long winter. I can think of many other things in nature that would have given it a much more horrible end than I did. A cow stuck in the same environment as the moose wouldn't last a week. So what do you prepose? We let loose all the cows and give them their god given right to freedom?<br>
<br>
